frequencies <- function(vec){
 # get the length of the vector we are using in the calclations.   
 len_vec <- length(vec)   

 # Create vector to store evolving averages 
 avg <- 1:len_vec
 
 # loop through to compute the averages. We compute the averages by counting the number of   
 for(i in 1:len_vec){
     avg[i] <- length(which(vec[1:i]==1))/i
 }  
  return(avg)  
}

estimate_pi <- function(seed = 1, iterations = 100000000) {
  #setting seed for reproducibility
  set.seed(seed)
  
  #generating the points
  
  x <- runif(n = iterations, min = 0, max = 1)
  
  #Computing an approximation for pi /4
  
  val_of_g = sqrt(1-x^2)
  
  pi_over_four = mean(val_of_g)  
  
  #estimating pi using formula pi = 4*the mean
  
  pi <- 4 * pi_over_four
  return(pi)
  
}

# Function that mimics the lottery and graphs 
lottery <- function(seed = 1, iterations = 15000) {
  
#Set seed for reproducibility
  set.seed(seed)
  
#generate n sets of ticket numbers where a ticket number is a set of three
#integers between 1 and 4 inclusive
  num1 <- floor(runif(n = iterations, min = 1, max = 4))
  num2 <- floor(runif(n = iterations, min = 1, max = 4))
  num3 <- floor(runif(n = iterations, min = 1, max = 4))
  
#Calculate sum of each ticket
  sum <- num1 + num2 + num3
  
#Create dataframe with ticket numbers in order to make easier to graph
  ticket <- 100*num1 + 10*num2 + num3
  ticket <- as.data.frame(ticket)
  
#Count occurrences of each ticket number
  df <- ticket %>%
    group_by(ticket) %>%
    summarise(counts = n())
  
#Graphs occurrences of each ticket number 
    df$ticket <- as.factor(df$ticket)
    p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = ticket, y = counts)) +
      geom_bar(fill = "#0073C2FF", stat='identity') + 
      theme_bw()
    print(p)
    
  return(list(df, table(sum)))  
}
lottery()

1.) Consider an experiment where you toss a a fair coin 15 times. Let X be the number of heads that you obtain. Note that X~Bin(15, 1/2).

1a.) Compute P(X=7) (using the formulas associated with the binomial distributions. R can compute the theoretical value as well if you choose to go that route)

#using P(X=k) = (n choose k)*(p^k)*(1-p)^(n-k) for X~Bin(n,p), we can calculate P(X=7) as follows:
prob_xis7 <- choose(15, 7)*(0.5)^7*(1-0.5)^(15-7)
prob_xis7
## [1] 0.1963806

1b.) Plot the evolution of the relative frequency for X=7 based on 100,000 repetitions of the above.

set.seed(25)
seven_heads <- rbinom(100000, 1, prob_xis7)

Data <- data.frame(trial_number = (1:length(seven_heads)), trial_result = seven_heads)

frequencies <- function(vec) {
  len_vec <- length(vec)

1c.) Explain how your observations match up with the frequentist interpretation of probability.

We can see that in the early trials, the relative frequency for X=7 deviates considerably from the true probability of getting 7 heads (~0.1963806), and jumps both above and below this value. However, as the number of trials increases, the relative frequency stabilizes and gets closer to this true probability. This matches up with the frequentist interpretation of probability, which states that as the number of trials increases, the relative frequency of getting a particular outcome gets closer to the true probability of getting that outcome.

1e.) Do your observations match up with the law of large numbers?

The observed average of the repetitions, 7.49845, is very close to the expected value of X (E(X) = 7.5). This matches up with the law of large numbers, which states that for almost every large sample x1,,xn obtained using the distribution of X, the sum from i=1 to n of xi/n is approximately equal to E(X). In simpler words, the larger the sample size of a sample taken from the distribution of a random variable X, the closer the sample mean is to E(X).

2.) Experimentally verify the law of large numbers for the standard normal distribution and an exponential distribution with =5.

set.seed(25)
small_normal <- rnorm(10)
mean(small_normal)
## [1] -0.1743769
large_normal <- rnorm(100000)
mean(large_normal)
## [1] 0.0009338873
small_exp <- rexp(10, rate=5)
mean(small_exp)
## [1] 0.2189413
large_exp <- rexp(100000, rate=5)
mean(large_exp)
## [1] 0.2003544

For X~Normal(0,1), E(X)=0. We can see that when the sample size is 10, the sample mean of -0.1743769 is somewhat, but not very, close to this E(X). However, when the sample size is 100000, the sample mean of 0.0009338873 is very close to this E(X). For X~Exp(5), E(X)=1/5=0.2. As with the normal distribution, we can see that for a sample of 10, the sample mean of 0.2189413 is only somewhat close to this E(X). However, for a sample of 100000, the sample mean of 0.2003544 is very close to this E(X). This verifies the law of large numbers for these distributions, which states that for a sufficiently large sample from the distribution of a random variable, the sample mean is approximately equal to the expected value of the random variable.

lottery <- function(seed = 25, iterations = 15000) {

  set.seed(seed)
  
#generate n sets of ticket numbers where a ticket number is a set of three

  num1 <- floor(runif(n = iterations, min = 1, max = 4))
  num2 <- floor(runif(n = iterations, min = 1, max = 4))
  num3 <- floor(runif(n = iterations, min = 1, max = 4))
  
#Calculate sum of each ticket
  sum <- num1 + num2 + num3
  
#Create dataframe with ticket numbers in order to make easier to graph
  ticket <- 100*num1 + 10*num2 + num3
  ticket <- as.data.frame(ticket)
  
#Count occurrences of each ticket number
  df <- ticket %>%
    group_by(ticket) %>%
    summarise(counts = n())
  
#Graphs occurrences of each ticket number 
    df$ticket <- as.factor(df$ticket)
    p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = ticket, y = counts)) +
      geom_bar(fill = "#0073C2FF", stat='identity') + 
      theme_bw()
    print(p)
    
#Count occurrences of each sum
    df2 <- data.frame(sum=sum) %>%
      group_by(sum) %>%
      summarise(sum_counts = n())
    
#Graph occurrences of each sum
    df2$sum <- as.factor(df2$sum)
    sums_plot <- ggplot(df2, aes(x = sum, y = sum_counts)) +
      geom_bar(fill = "#000000", stat='identity') + 
      theme_bw()
    print(sums_plot)
  
    return(list(df, table(sum)))  
}

The distribution of the sums appears bell-shaped with a center around 6. The distribution is symmetrical with a peak at 6, and as we move farther from this center in either direction the frequency of the sum decreases. Its notable that the distribution is centered around the expected value of the sum, 3[1(1/3)+2(1/3)+3(1/3)]=6. The distribution suggests that 6 is the most common sum, followed by 5 and 7, then 4 and 8, then 3 and 9. Intuitively, this makes sense, as there are more tickets whose digits sum to 6 (123, 132, 213, 222, 231, 312, 321 > 7 unique tickets) than any other number. It also makes sense that there are approximately 7 times as many sums of 6 as there are sums of 3 (3857/533 7), since there are 7 unique tickets whose digits sum to 6 and only 1 unique ticket whose digits sum to 3 (111), and each ticket has an equal likelihood of being selected.

4.) (Monte Carlo Methods):

4a.) Estimate the value of by considering X~U[-1,1] and g(x) = (1-x^2). You will need to factor in fX(x) = 1/2 for x [-1,1]; 0 otherwise when you use the estimate. You should use an n that is at least 1,000,000.

pi_estimation <- function(seed = 25, iterations = 100000000) {
  #setting seed for reproducibility
  set.seed(seed)
  
  #generating the points
  x <- runif(n = iterations, min = -1, max = 1)
  
  #computing an approximation for pi/4
  val_of_g = sqrt(1-x^2)
  pi_over_four = mean(val_of_g)
  
  #estimating pi using formula pi = 4*the mean
  pi <- 4 * pi_over_four
  return(pi)
}

pi_estimation()
## [1] 3.141601

4b.) Estimate the value of the integral from 0 to 2 of (1 + t^2 + t^4)dt using a similar approach to (a)

estimate_integral <- function(seed = 25, iterations = 100000000) {
  set.seed(seed)
  t <- runif(n = iterations, min = 0, max = 2)
  val_of_g = sqrt(1+t^2+t^4)
  
  #computing an approximation for half of the integral, since the full integral is evaluated from 0 to 2
  half_estimate <- mean(val_of_g)
  
  #estimating the full value of the integral by multiplying the mean by the length of the interval, 2
  full_estimate <- 2 * half_estimate
  return(full_estimate)
}

estimate_integral()
## [1] 4.194315

5.) Simulate 10000 repetitions each for X~Bin(21, 3/5) and Y~Bin(19, 3/5). Draw a relative frequency histogram. Does the outcome seem to support X+Y ~ Bin(40, 3/5)? Discuss your answer.

set.seed(25)
X <- rbinom(10000, 21, 3/5)
df_X <- data.frame(X=X) %>%
    group_by(X) %>%
    summarise(X_counts = n())
df_X$X <- as.factor(df_X$X)
    X_plot <- ggplot(df_X, aes(x = X, y = X_counts/10000)) +
      geom_bar(fill = "#800080", stat='identity') + 
      labs(y = 'relative frequency') +
      theme_bw()

Y <- rbinom(10000, 19, 3/5)
df_Y <- data.frame(Y=Y) %>%
    group_by(Y) %>%
    summarise(Y_counts = n())
df_Y$Y <- as.factor(df_Y$Y)
    Y_plot <- ggplot(df_Y, aes(x = Y, y = Y_counts/10000)) +
      geom_bar(fill = "#008000", stat='identity') +
      labs(y = 'relative frequency') +
      theme_bw()
    
df_XplusY <- data.frame(XplusY=(X+Y)) %>%
    group_by(XplusY) %>%
    summarise(XplusY_counts = n())
    XplusY_plot <- ggplot(df_XplusY, aes(x = XplusY, y = XplusY_counts/10000)) +
      geom_bar(fill = "#808000", stat='identity') +
      labs(y = 'relative frequency') +
      xlim(7,39) +
      theme_bw()
    
Z <- rbinom(100000000, 40, 3/5)
df_Z <- data.frame(Z=Z) %>%
    group_by(Z) %>%
    summarise(Z_counts = n())
df_Z$Z <- as.factor(df_Z$Z)
    Z_plot <- ggplot(df_Z, aes(x = Z, y = Z_counts/100000000)) +
      geom_bar(fill = "#000080", stat='identity') +
      labs(y = 'relative frequency') +
      theme_bw()
    
print(X_plot)

print(Y_plot)

print(XplusY_plot)

print(Z_plot)

This outcome does seem to support that X+Y ~ Bin(40, 3/5). The third histogram shows the distribution of 10000 trials of X+Y, where X~Bin(21, 3/5) and Y~Bin(19, 3/5). The fourth histogram shows the distribution of 100000000 trials of Z, where Z~Bin(40, 3/5). Since the number of trials for Z is so large, we can say that the distribution of these 100000000 trials is very close to the true distribution of a binomial random variable with parameters n=40, p=3/5. This distribution also appears very similar to the distribution of X+Y in the third histogram: both distributions are centered around 24 with a very similar bell shape. The strong similarity between the distributions seems to support the statement X+Y ~ Bin(40, 3/5), although we cannot say this with absolute certainty just based on the similarity between distributions.
